# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: response-surface-methodology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] In statistics, **Box–Behnken designs** are experimental designs for response surface methodology, devised by George E.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Box-Behnken design is still considered to be more proficient and more powerful than other designs such as the three-level full factorial design, central composite design (CCD) and Doehlert design, despite its poor coverage of the corner of nonlinear design space.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] The design with 7 factors was found first while looking for a design having the desired property concerning estimation variance, and then similar designs were found for other numbers of factors.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Each design can be thought of as a combination of a two-level (full or fractional) factorial design with an incomplete block design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] In each block, a certain number of factors are put through all combinations for the factorial design, while the other factors are kept at the central values.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] For instance, the Box–Behnken design for 3 factors involves three blocks, in each of which 2 factors are varied through the 4 possible combinations of high and low.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] It is necessary to include centre points as well (in which all factors are at their central values).
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] In this table, *m* represents the number of factors which are varied in each of the blocks.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] The design for 8 factors was not in the original paper.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Taking the 9 factor design, deleting one column and any resulting duplicate rows produces an 81 run design for 8 factors, while giving up some "rotatability" (see above).
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Designs for other numbers of factors have also been invented (at least up to 21).
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] A design for 16 factors exists having only 256 factorial points.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Using Plackett–Burmans to construct a 16 factor design (see below) requires only 221 points.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Most of these designs can be split into groups (blocks), for each of which the model will have a different constant term, in such a way that the block constants will be uncorrelated with the other coefficients.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Plackett–Burman designs can be used, replacing the fractional factorial and incomplete block designs, to construct smaller or larger Box–Behnkens, in which case, axial points of length *α* = ((*K* + 1)/2)1/2 better approximate original design points' distances from the centre.
[src:response-surface-methodology/box-behnken-design] Since each column of the basic design has 50% 0s and 25% each +1s and −1s, multiplying each column, *j*, by *σ*(*X**j*)·21/2 and adding *μ*(*X**j*) prior to experimentation, under a general linear model hypothesis, produces a "sample" of output Y with correct first and second moments of *Y*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] In statistics, a **central composite design** is an experimental design, useful in response surface methodology, for building a second order (quadratic) model for the response variable without needing to use a complete three-level factorial experiment.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] After the designed experiment is performed, linear regression is used, sometimes iteratively, to obtain results.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] Coded variables are often used when constructing this design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] A set of *center points*, experimental runs whose values of each factor are the medians of the values used in the factorial portion.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] A set of *axial points*, experimental runs identical to the centre points except for one factor, which will take on values both below and above the median of the two factorial levels, and typically both outside their range.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] The matrix **C** from the center points, denoted in coded variables as (0,0,0,...,0), where there are *k* zeros.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] A matrix **E** from the axial points, with 2*k* rows.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] Each factor is sequentially placed at ±α and all other factors are at zero.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] The value of α is determined by the designer; while arbitrary, some values may give the design desirable properties.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] where **d**(*i*) represents the *i*th column in **d**.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] There are many different methods to select a useful value of α.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] Let *F* be the number of points due to the factorial design and *T* = 2*k* + *n*, the number of additional points, where *n* is the number of central points in the design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] **Rotatable design**: α = *F*1/4 (the design implemented by MATLAB’s *ccdesign* function).
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] Statistical approaches such as Response Surface Methodology can be employed to maximize the production of a special substance by optimization of operational factors.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] In contrast to conventional methods, the interaction among process variables can be determined by statistical techniques.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] For instance, in a study, a central composite design was employed to investigate the effect of critical parameters of organosolv pretreatment of rice straw including temperature, time, and ethanol concentration.
[src:response-surface-methodology/central-composite-design] The residual solid, lignin recovery, and hydrogen yield were selected as the response variables.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In the more general approach, an optimization problem consists of maximizing or minimizing a real function by systematically choosing input values from within an allowed set and computing the value of the function.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The generalization of optimization theory and techniques to other formulations constitutes a large area of applied mathematics.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Such a formulation is called an **optimization problem** or a **mathematical programming problem** (a term not directly related to computer programming, but still in use for example in linear programming – see History below).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Many real-world and theoretical problems may be modeled in this general framework.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] it suffices to solve only minimization problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] However, the opposite perspective of considering only maximization problems would be valid, too.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Problems formulated using this technique in the fields of physics may refer to the technique as *energy minimization*, speaking of the value of the function f as representing the energy of the system being modeled.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In machine learning, it is always necessary to continuously evaluate the quality of a data model by using a cost function where a minimum implies a set of possibly optimal parameters with an optimal (lowest) error.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Typically, A is some subset of the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , often specified by a set of *constraints*, equalities or inequalities that the members of A have to satisfy.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The domain A of f is called the *search space* or the *choice set*, while the elements of A are called *candidate solutions* or *feasible solutions*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The function f is variously called an *objective function*, *criterion function*, *loss function*, *cost function* (minimization), *utility function* or *fitness function* (maximization), or, in certain fields, an *energy function* or *energy functional*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] A feasible solution that minimizes (or maximizes) the objective function is called an *optimal solution*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In mathematics, conventional optimization problems are usually stated in terms of minimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] that is to say, on some region around **x*** all of the function values are greater than or equal to the value at that element.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] While a local minimum is at least as good as any nearby elements, a global minimum is at least as good as every feasible element.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Generally, unless the objective function is convex in a minimization problem, there may be several local minima.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In a convex problem, if there is a local minimum that is interior (not on the edge of the set of feasible elements), it is also the global minimum, but a nonconvex problem may have more than one local minimum not all of which need be global minima.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Global optimization is the branch of applied mathematics and numerical analysis that is concerned with the development of deterministic algorithms that are capable of guaranteeing convergence in finite time to the actual optimal solution of a nonconvex problem.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often expressed with special notation.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] This denotes the minimum value of the objective function *x*2 + 1, when choosing x from the set of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The minimum value in this case is 1, occurring at *x* = 0.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] asks for the maximum value of the objective function 2*x*, where x may be any real number.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In this case, there is no such maximum as the objective function is unbounded, so the answer is "infinity" or "undefined".
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] This represents the value (or values) of the argument x in the interval (−∞,−1] that minimizes (or minimize) the objective function *x*2 + 1 (the actual minimum value of that function is not what the problem asks for).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the answer is *x* = −1, since *x* = 0 is infeasible, that is, it does not belong to the feasible set.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] represents the {*x*, *y*} pair (or pairs) that maximizes (or maximize) the value of the objective function *x* cos *y*, with the added constraint that x lie in the interval [−5,5] (again, the actual maximum value of the expression does not matter).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the solutions are the pairs of the form {5, 2*k*π} and {−5, (2*k* + 1)π}, where k ranges over all integers.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Operators arg min and arg max are sometimes also written as argmin and argmax, and stand for *argument of the minimum* and *argument of the maximum*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Fermat and Lagrange found calculus-based formulae for identifying optima, while Newton and Gauss proposed iterative methods for moving towards an optimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The term "linear programming" for certain optimization cases was due to George B.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Dantzig, although much of the theory had been introduced by Leonid Kantorovich in 1939.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Adding more than one objective to an optimization problem adds complexity.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] For example, to optimize a structural design, one would desire a design that is both light and rigid.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] When two objectives conflict, a trade-off must be created.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] There may be one lightest design, one stiffest design, and an infinite number of designs that are some compromise of weight and rigidity.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The set of trade-off designs that improve upon one criterion at the expense of another is known as the Pareto set.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The curve created plotting weight against stiffness of the best designs is known as the Pareto frontier.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] A design is judged to be "Pareto optimal" (equivalently, "Pareto efficient" or in the Pareto set) if it is not dominated by any other design: If it is worse than another design in some respects and no better in any respect, then it is dominated and is not Pareto optimal.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The choice among "Pareto optimal" solutions to determine the "favorite solution" is delegated to the decision maker.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In other words, defining the problem as multi-objective optimization signals that some information is missing: desirable objectives are given but combinations of them are not rated relative to each other.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the missing information can be derived by interactive sessions with the decision maker.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Multi-objective optimization problems have been generalized further into vector optimization problems where the (partial) ordering is no longer given by the Pareto ordering.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often multi-modal; that is, they possess multiple good solutions.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] They could all be globally good (same cost function value) or there could be a mix of globally good and locally good solutions.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Obtaining all (or at least some of) the multiple solutions is the goal of a multi-modal optimizer.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Classical optimization techniques due to their iterative approach do not perform satisfactorily when they are used to obtain multiple solutions, since it is not guaranteed that different solutions will be obtained even with different starting points in multiple runs of the algorithm.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Common approaches to global optimization problems, where multiple local extrema may be present include evolutionary algorithms, Bayesian optimization and simulated annealing.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The *satisfiability problem*, also called the *feasibility problem*, is just the problem of finding any feasible solution at all without regard to objective value.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] This can be regarded as the special case of mathematical optimization where the objective value is the same for every solution, and thus any solution is optimal.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Many optimization algorithms need to start from a feasible point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] One way to obtain such a point is to relax the feasibility conditions using a slack variable; with enough slack, any starting point is feasible.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Then, minimize that slack variable until the slack is null or negative.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The extreme value theorem of Karl Weierstrass states that a continuous real-valued function on a compact set attains its maximum and minimum value.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a lower semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its minimum; an upper semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its maximum point or view.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] One of Fermat's theorems states that optima of unconstrained problems are found at stationary points, where the first derivative or the gradient of the objective function is zero (see first derivative test).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] More generally, they may be found at critical points, where the first derivative or gradient of the objective function is zero or is undefined, or on the boundary of the choice set.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] An equation (or set of equations) stating that the first derivative(s) equal(s) zero at an interior optimum is called a 'first-order condition' or a set of first-order conditions.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optima of equality-constrained problems can be found by the Lagrange multiplier method.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The optima of problems with equality and/or inequality constraints can be found using the 'Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions'.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] While the first derivative test identifies points that might be extrema, this test does not distinguish a point that is a minimum from one that is a maximum or one that is neither.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The conditions that distinguish maxima, or minima, from other stationary points are called 'second-order conditions' (see 'Second derivative test').
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] If a candidate solution satisfies the first-order conditions, then the satisfaction of the second-order conditions as well is sufficient to establish at least local optimality.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The envelope theorem describes how the value of an optimal solution changes when an underlying parameter changes.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The process of computing this change is called comparative statics.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The maximum theorem of Claude Berge (1963) describes the continuity of an optimal solution as a function of underlying parameters.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] For unconstrained problems with twice-differentiable functions, some critical points can be found by finding the points where the gradient of the objective function is zero (that is, the stationary points).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a zero subgradient certifies that a local minimum has been found for minimization problems with convex functions and other locally Lipschitz functions, which meet in loss function minimization of the neural network.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The positive-negative momentum estimation lets to avoid the local minimum and converges at the objective function global minimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Constrained problems can often be transformed into unconstrained problems with the help of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Lagrangian relaxation can also provide approximate solutions to difficult constrained problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] When the objective function is a convex function, then any local minimum will also be a global minimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] There exist efficient numerical techniques for minimizing convex functions, such as interior-point methods.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] More generally, if the objective function is not a quadratic function, then many optimization methods use other methods to ensure that some subsequence of iterations converges to an optimal solution.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The first and still popular method for ensuring convergence relies on line searches, which optimize a function along one dimension.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] A second and increasingly popular method for ensuring convergence uses trust regions.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Both line searches and trust regions are used in modern methods of non-differentiable optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Usually, a global optimizer is much slower than advanced local optimizers (such as BFGS), so often an efficient global optimizer can be constructed by starting the local optimizer from different starting points.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] To solve problems, researchers may use algorithms that terminate in a finite number of steps, or iterative methods that converge to a solution (on some specified class of problems), or heuristics that may provide approximate solutions to some problems (although their iterates need not converge).
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The iterative methods used to solve problems of nonlinear programming differ according to whether they evaluate Hessians, gradients, or only function values.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] While evaluating Hessians (H) and gradients (G) improves the rate of convergence, for functions for which these quantities exist and vary sufficiently smoothly, such evaluations increase the computational complexity (or computational cost) of each iteration.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the computational complexity may be excessively high.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] One major criterion for optimizers is just the number of required function evaluations as this often is already a large computational effort, usually much more effort than within the optimizer itself, which mainly has to operate over the N variables.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The derivatives provide detailed information for such optimizers, but are even harder to calculate, e.g. approximating the gradient takes at least N+1 function evaluations.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] For approximations of the 2nd derivatives (collected in the Hessian matrix), the number of function evaluations is in the order of N².
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Newton's method requires the 2nd-order derivatives, so for each iteration, the number of function calls is in the order of N², but for a simpler pure gradient optimizer it is only N.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] However, gradient optimizers need usually more iterations than Newton's algorithm.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Which one is best with respect to the number of function calls depends on the problem itself.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Besides (finitely terminating) algorithms and (convergent) iterative methods, there are heuristics.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] A heuristic is any algorithm which is not guaranteed (mathematically) to find the solution, but which is nevertheless useful in certain practical situations.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Also, the problem of computing contact forces can be done by solving a linear complementarity problem, which can also be viewed as a QP (quadratic programming) problem.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Many design problems can also be expressed as optimization programs.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] This application is called design optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] One subset is the engineering optimization, and another recent and growing subset of this field is multidisciplinary design optimization, which, while useful in many problems, has in particular been applied to aerospace engineering problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] This approach may be applied in cosmology and astrophysics.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Economics is closely enough linked to optimization of agents that an influential definition relatedly describes economics *qua* science as the "study of human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means" with alternative uses.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Modern optimization theory includes traditional optimization theory but also overlaps with game theory and the study of economic equilibria.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The *Journal of Economic Literature* codes classify mathematical programming, optimization techniques, and related topics under JEL:C61-C63.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] In microeconomics, the utility maximization problem and its dual problem, the expenditure minimization problem, are economic optimization problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Insofar as they behave consistently, consumers are assumed to maximize their utility, while firms are usually assumed to maximize their profit.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Also, agents are often modeled as being risk-averse, thereby preferring to avoid risk.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Asset prices are also modeled using optimization theory, though the underlying mathematics relies on optimizing stochastic processes rather than on static optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] International trade theory also uses optimization to explain trade patterns between nations.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The optimization of portfolios is an example of multi-objective optimization in economics.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Since the 1970s, economists have modeled dynamic decisions over time using control theory.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] For example, dynamic search models are used to study labor-market behavior.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] A crucial distinction is between deterministic and stochastic models.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Macroeconomists build dynamic stochastic general equilibrium (DSGE) models that describe the dynamics of the whole economy as the result of the interdependent optimizing decisions of workers, consumers, investors, and governments.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Some common applications of optimization techniques in electrical engineering include active filter design, stray field reduction in superconducting magnetic energy storage systems, space mapping design of microwave structures, handset antennas, electromagnetics-based design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Electromagnetically validated design optimization of microwave components and antennas has made extensive use of an appropriate physics-based or empirical surrogate model and space mapping methodologies since the discovery of space mapping in 1993.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are also used in power-flow analysis.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization has been widely used in civil engineering.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Construction management and transportation engineering are among the main branches of civil engineering that heavily rely on optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The most common civil engineering problems that are solved by optimization are cut and fill of roads, life-cycle analysis of structures and infrastructures, resource leveling, water resource allocation, traffic management and schedule optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Another field that uses optimization techniques extensively is operations research.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Operations research also uses stochastic modeling and simulation to support improved decision-making.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Increasingly, operations research uses stochastic programming to model dynamic decisions that adapt to events; such problems can be solved with large-scale optimization and stochastic optimization methods.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Mathematical optimization is used in much modern controller design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] High-level controllers such as model predictive control (MPC) or real-time optimization (RTO) employ mathematical optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] These algorithms run online and repeatedly determine values for decision variables, such as choke openings in a process plant, by iteratively solving a mathematical optimization problem including constraints and a model of the system to be controlled.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are regularly used in geophysical parameter estimation problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Given a set of geophysical measurements, e.g. seismic recordings, it is common to solve for the physical properties and geometrical shapes of the underlying rocks and fluids.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] The majority of problems in geophysics are nonlinear with both deterministic and stochastic methods being widely used.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear optimization methods are widely used in conformational analysis.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are used in many facets of computational systems biology such as model building, optimal experimental design, metabolic engineering, and synthetic biology.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Linear programming has been applied to calculate the maximal possible yields of fermentation products, and to infer gene regulatory networks from multiple microarray datasets as well as transcriptional regulatory networks from high-throughput data.
[src:response-surface-methodology/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear programming has been used to analyze energy metabolism and has been applied to metabolic engineering and parameter estimation in biochemical pathways.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In the design of experiments, **optimal experimental designs** (or **optimum designs**) are a class of experimental designs that are optimal with respect to some statistical criterion.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The creation of this field of statistics has been credited to Danish statistician Kirstine Smith.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In the design of experiments for estimating statistical models, **optimal designs** allow parameters to be estimated without bias and with minimum variance.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] A non-optimal design requires a greater number of experimental runs to estimate the parameters with the same precision as an optimal design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In practical terms, optimal experiments can reduce the costs of experimentation.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The optimality of a design depends on the statistical model and is assessed with respect to a statistical criterion, which is related to the variance-matrix of the estimator.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Specifying an appropriate model and specifying a suitable criterion function both require understanding of statistical theory and practical knowledge with designing experiments.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Optimal designs can accommodate multiple types of factors, such as process, mixture, and discrete factors.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Designs can be optimized when the design-space is constrained, for example, when the mathematical process-space contains factor-settings that are practically infeasible (e.g. due to safety concerns).
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Experimental designs are evaluated using statistical criteria.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] It is known that the least squares estimator minimizes the variance of mean-unbiased estimators (under the conditions of the Gauss–Markov theorem).
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In the estimation theory for statistical models with one real parameter, the reciprocal of the variance of an ("efficient") estimator is called the "Fisher information" for that estimator.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Because of this reciprocity, ***minimizing* the *variance*** corresponds to ***maximizing* the *information***.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] When the statistical model has several parameters, however, the mean of the parameter-estimator is a vector and its variance is a matrix.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The inverse matrix of the variance-matrix is called the "information matrix".
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Because the variance of the estimator of a parameter vector is a matrix, the problem of "minimizing the variance" is complicated.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Using statistical theory, statisticians compress the information-matrix using real-valued summary statistics; being real-valued functions, these "information criteria" can be maximized.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The traditional optimality-criteria are invariants of the information matrix; algebraically, the traditional optimality-criteria are functionals of the eigenvalues of the information matrix.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In many applications, the statistician is most concerned with a "parameter of interest" rather than with "nuisance parameters".
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] More generally, statisticians consider linear combinations of parameters, which are estimated via linear combinations of treatment-means in the design of experiments and in the analysis of variance; such linear combinations are called contrasts.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Statisticians can use appropriate optimality-criteria for such parameters of interest and for contrasts.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Catalogs of optimal designs occur in books and in software libraries.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In addition, major statistical systems like SAS and R have procedures for optimizing a design according to a user's specification.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The experimenter must specify a model for the design and an optimality-criterion before the method can compute an optimal design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Some advanced topics in optimal design require more statistical theory and practical knowledge in designing experiments.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Since the optimality criterion of most optimal designs is based on some function of the information matrix, the 'optimality' of a given design is *model dependent*: While an optimal design is best for that model, its performance may deteriorate on other models.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] On other models, an *optimal* design can be either better or worse than a non-optimal design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Therefore, it is important to benchmark the performance of designs under alternative models.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The choice of an appropriate optimality criterion requires some thought, and it is useful to benchmark the performance of designs with respect to several optimality criteria.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Indeed, there are several classes of designs for which all the traditional optimality-criteria agree, according to the theory of "universal optimality" of Kiefer.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The experience of practitioners like Cornell and the "universal optimality" theory of Kiefer suggest that robustness with respect to changes in the *optimality-criterion* is much greater than is robustness with respect to changes in the *model*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] High-quality statistical software provide a combination of libraries of optimal designs or iterative methods for constructing approximately optimal designs, depending on the model specified and the optimality criterion.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Users may use a standard optimality-criterion or may program a custom-made criterion.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] All of the traditional optimality-criteria are convex (or concave) functions, and therefore optimal-designs are amenable to the mathematical theory of convex analysis and their computation can use specialized methods of convex minimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The practitioner need not select *exactly one* traditional, optimality-criterion, but can specify a custom criterion.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In particular, the practitioner can specify a convex criterion using the maxima of convex optimality-criteria and nonnegative combinations of optimality criteria (since these operations preserve convex functions).
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] For *convex* optimality criteria, the Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence theorem allows the practitioner to verify that a given design is globally optimal.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence theorem is related with the Legendre-Fenchel conjugacy for convex functions.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] If an optimality-criterion lacks convexity, then finding a global optimum and verifying its optimality often are difficult.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] When scientists wish to test several theories, then a statistician can design an experiment that allows optimal tests between specified models.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Such "discrimination experiments" are especially important in the biostatistics supporting pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics, following the work of Cox and Atkinson.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] When practitioners need to consider multiple models, they can specify a probability-measure on the models and then select any design maximizing the expected value of such an experiment.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Such probability-based optimal-designs are called optimal Bayesian designs.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Such Bayesian designs are used especially for generalized linear models (where the response follows an exponential-family distribution).
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The use of a Bayesian design does not force statisticians to use Bayesian methods to analyze the data, however.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Indeed, the "Bayesian" label for probability-based experimental-designs is disliked by some researchers.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Alternative terminology for "Bayesian" optimality includes "on-average" optimality or "population" optimality.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Scientific experimentation is an iterative process, and statisticians have developed several approaches to the optimal design of sequential experiments.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Sequential analysis was pioneered by Abraham Wald.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In 1972, Herman Chernoff wrote an overview of optimal sequential designs, while adaptive designs were surveyed later by S.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Of course, much work on the optimal design of experiments is related to the theory of optimal decisions, especially the statistical decision theory of Abraham Wald.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Optimal designs for response-surface models are discussed in the textbook by Atkinson, Donev and Tobias, and in the survey of Gaffke and Heiligers and in the mathematical text of Pukelsheim.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The blocking of optimal designs is discussed in the textbook of Atkinson, Donev and Tobias and also in the monograph by Goos.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The earliest optimal designs were developed to estimate the parameters of regression models with continuous variables, for example, by J.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In English, two early contributions were made by Charles S.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Pioneering designs for multivariate response-surfaces were proposed by George E.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] However, Box's designs have few optimality properties.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Indeed, the Box–Behnken design requires excessive experimental runs when the number of variables exceeds three.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Box's "central-composite" designs require more experimental runs than do the optimal designs of Kôno.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The optimization of sequential experimentation is studied also in stochastic programming and in systems and control.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Popular methods include stochastic approximation and other methods of stochastic optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Much of this research has been associated with the subdiscipline of system identification.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Nemirovskii and Boris Polyak has described methods that are more efficient than the (Armijo-style) step-size rules introduced by G.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Adaptive designs are used in clinical trials, and optimal adaptive designs are surveyed in the *Handbook of Experimental Designs* chapter by Shelemyahu Zacks.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] There are several methods of finding an optimal design, given an *a priori* restriction on the number of experimental runs or replications.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Some of these methods are discussed by Atkinson, Donev and Tobias and in the paper by Hardin and Sloane.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Of course, fixing the number of experimental runs *a priori* would be impractical.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Prudent statisticians examine the other optimal designs, whose number of experimental runs differ.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In the mathematical theory on optimal experiments, an optimal design can be a probability measure that is supported on an infinite set of observation-locations.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Such optimal probability-measure designs solve a mathematical problem that neglected to specify the cost of observations and experimental runs.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Nonetheless, such optimal probability-measure designs can be discretized to furnish approximately optimal designs.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In some cases, a finite set of observation-locations suffices to support an optimal design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Such a result was proved by Kôno and Kiefer in their works on response-surface designs for quadratic models.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] The Kôno–Kiefer analysis explains why optimal designs for response-surfaces can have discrete supports, which are very similar as do the less efficient designs that have been traditional in response surface methodology.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] In 1815, an article on optimal designs for polynomial regression was published by Joseph Diaz Gergonne, according to Stigler.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Peirce proposed an economic theory of scientific experimentation in 1876, which sought to maximize the precision of the estimates.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Peirce's optimal allocation immediately improved the accuracy of gravitational experiments and was used for decades by Peirce and his colleagues.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] Kirstine Smith proposed optimal designs for polynomial models in 1918.
[src:response-surface-methodology/optimal-design] (Kirstine Smith had been a student of the Danish statistician Thorvald N.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] In statistics, **response surface methodology** (**RSM**) explores the relationships between several explanatory variables and one or more response variables.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] RSM is an empirical model which employs the use of mathematical and statistical techniques to relate input variables, otherwise known as factors, to the response.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] RSM became very useful because other methods available, such as the theoretical model, could be very cumbersome to use, time-consuming, inefficient, error-prone, and unreliable.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] The main idea of RSM is to use a sequence of designed experiments to obtain an optimal response.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Box and Wilson suggest using a second-degree polynomial model to do this.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] They acknowledge that this model is only an approximation, but they use it because such a model is easy to estimate and apply, even when little is known about the process.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Statistical approaches such as RSM can be employed to maximize the production of a special substance by optimization of operational factors.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Of late, for formulation optimization, the RSM, using proper **design of experiments** (**DoE**), has become extensively used.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] An easy way to estimate a first-degree polynomial model is to use a factorial experiment or a fractional factorial design.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] This is sufficient to determine which explanatory variables affect the response variable(s) of interest.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Once it is suspected that only significant explanatory variables are left, then a more complicated design, such as a central composite design can be implemented to estimate a second-degree polynomial model, which is still only an approximation at best.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] However, the second-degree model can be used to optimize (maximize, minimize, or attain a specific target for) the response variable(s) of interest.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] The property that allows individual effects of the k-factors to be estimated independently without (or with minimal) confounding.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Also orthogonality provides minimum variance estimates of the model coefficient so that they are uncorrelated.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] The property of rotating points of the design about the center of the factor space.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] The moments of the distribution of the design points are constant.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] A third property of CCD designs used to control the number of center points is uniform precision (or Uniformity).
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Cubic designs are discussed by Kiefer, by Atkinson, Donev, and Tobias and by Hardin and Sloane.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Spherical designs are discussed by Kiefer and by Hardin and Sloane.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Mixture experiments are discussed in many books on the design of experiments, and in the response-surface methodology textbooks of Box and Draper and of Atkinson, Donev and Tobias.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] An extensive discussion and survey appears in the advanced textbook by John Cornell.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Some extensions of response surface methodology deal with the multiple response problem.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Multiple response variables create difficulty because what is optimal for one response may not be optimal for other responses.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Other extensions are used to reduce variability in a single response while targeting a specific value, or attaining a near maximum or minimum while preventing variability in that response from getting too large.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Response surface methodology uses statistical models, and therefore practitioners need to be aware that even the best statistical model is an approximation to reality.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] In practice, both the models and the parameter values are unknown, and subject to uncertainty on top of ignorance.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Of course, an estimated optimum point need not be optimum in reality, because of the errors of the estimates and of the inadequacies of the model.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Nonetheless, response surface methodology has an effective track-record of helping researchers improve products and services: For example, Box's original response-surface modeling enabled chemical engineers to improve a process that had been stuck at a saddle-point for years.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] The engineers had not been able to afford to fit a cubic three-level design to estimate a quadratic model, and their biased linear-models estimated the gradient to be zero.
[src:response-surface-methodology/response-surface-methodology] Box's design reduced the costs of experimentation so that a quadratic model could be fit, which led to a (long-sought) ascent direction.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The idea is to take repeated steps in the opposite direction of the gradient (or approximate gradient) of the function at the current point, because this is the direction of steepest descent.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Conversely, stepping in the direction of the gradient will lead to a trajectory that maximizes that function; the procedure is then known as *gradient ascent*.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent should not be confused with local search algorithms, although both are iterative methods for optimization.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent is particularly useful in machine learning and artificial intelligence for minimizing the cost or loss function.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent is generally attributed to Augustin-Louis Cauchy, who first suggested it in 1847.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Jacques Hadamard independently proposed a similar method in 1907.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Its convergence properties for non-linear optimization problems were first studied by Haskell Curry in 1944, with the method becoming increasingly well-studied and used in the following decades.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] A simple extension of gradient descent, stochastic gradient descent, serves as the most basic algorithm used for training most deep networks today.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] for a small enough step size or learning rate $\eta \in \mathbb {R} _{+}$ , then $f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )\geq f(\mathbf {a_{n+1}} )$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In other words, the term $\eta \nabla f(\mathbf {a} )$ is subtracted from $\mathbf {a}$ because we want to move against the gradient, toward the local minimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] so the sequence $(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ converges to the desired local minimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Note that the value of the *step size* $\eta$ is allowed to change at every iteration.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] It is possible to guarantee the convergence to a local minimum under certain assumptions on the function f (for example, f convex and $\nabla f$ Lipschitz) and particular choices of $\eta$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] as in the Barzilai-Borwein method, or a sequence $\eta _{n}$ satisfying the Wolfe conditions (which can be found by using line search).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] When the function f is convex, all local minima are also global minima, so in this case gradient descent can converge to the global solution.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] This process is illustrated in the adjacent picture.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Here, f is assumed to be defined on the plane, and that its graph has a bowl shape.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The blue curves are the contour lines, that is, the regions on which the value of f is constant.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] A red arrow originating at a point shows the direction of the negative gradient at that point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Note that the (negative) gradient at a point is orthogonal to the contour line going through that point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] We see that gradient *descent* leads us to the bottom of the bowl, that is, to the point where the value of the function f is minimal.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The basic intuition behind gradient descent can be illustrated by a hypothetical scenario.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] People are stuck in the mountains and are trying to get down (i.e., trying to find the global minimum).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] There is heavy fog such that visibility is extremely low.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Therefore, the path down the mountain is not visible, so they must use local information to find the minimum.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] They can use the method of gradient descent, which involves looking at the steepness of the hill at their current position, then proceeding in the direction with the steepest descent (i.e., downhill).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] If they were trying to find the top of the mountain (i.e., the maximum), then they would proceed in the direction of steepest ascent (i.e., uphill).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Using this method, they would eventually find their way down the mountain or possibly get stuck in some hole (i.e., local minimum or saddle point), like a mountain lake.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] However, assume also that the steepness of the hill is not immediately obvious with simple observation, but rather it requires a sophisticated instrument to measure, which the people happen to have at that moment.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] It takes quite some time to measure the steepness of the hill with the instrument.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Thus, they should minimize their use of the instrument if they want to get down the mountain before sunset.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The difficulty then is choosing the frequency at which they should measure the steepness of the hill so as not to go off track.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In this analogy, the people represent the algorithm, and the path taken down the mountain represents the sequence of parameter settings that the algorithm will explore.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The steepness of the hill represents the slope of the function at that point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The instrument used to measure steepness is differentiation.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The direction they choose to travel in aligns with the gradient of the function at that point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The amount of time they travel before taking another measurement is the step size.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Since using a step size $\eta$ that is too small would slow convergence, and a $\eta$ too large would lead to overshoot and divergence, finding a good setting of $\eta$ is an important practical problem.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Philip Wolfe also advocated using "clever choices of the [descent] direction" in practice.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] While using a direction that deviates from the steepest descent direction may seem counter-intuitive, the idea is that the smaller slope may be compensated for by being sustained over a much longer distance.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Finding good settings of $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ requires some thought.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] First of all, we would like the update direction to point downhill.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Mathematically, letting $\theta _{n}$ denote the angle between $-\nabla f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ , this requires that $\cos \theta _{n}>0.$ To say more, we need more information about the objective function that we are optimising.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] This inequality implies that the amount by which we can be sure the function f is decreased depends on a trade off between the two terms in square brackets.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The first term in square brackets measures the angle between the descent direction and the negative gradient.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The second term measures how quickly the gradient changes along the descent direction.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In principle inequality (**1**) could be optimized over $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ to choose an optimal step size and direction.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The problem is that evaluating the second term in square brackets requires evaluating $\nabla f(\mathbf {a} _{n}-t\eta _{n}\mathbf {p} _{n})$ , and extra gradient evaluations are generally expensive and undesirable.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Usually by following one of the recipes above, convergence to a local minimum can be guaranteed.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] reformulated as a quadratic minimization problem.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The line search minimization, finding the locally optimal step size $\eta$ on every iteration, can be performed analytically for quadratic functions, and explicit formulas for the locally optimal $\eta$ are known.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The method is rarely used for solving linear equations, with the conjugate gradient method being one of the most popular alternatives.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Both methods can benefit from preconditioning, where gradient descent may require less assumptions on the preconditioner.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Because each step is taken in the steepest direction, steepest-descent steps alternate between directions aligned with the extreme axes of the elongated level sets.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] When $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ is large, this produces a characteristic zig–zag path.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The poor conditioning of $\mathbf {A}$ is the primary cause of the slow convergence, and orthogonality of successive residuals reinforces this alternation.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] As shown in the image on the right, steepest descent converges slowly due to the high condition number of $\mathbf {A}$ , and the orthogonality of residuals forces each new direction to undo the overshoot from the previous step.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The result is a path that zigzags toward the solution.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] This inefficiency is one reason conjugate gradient or preconditioning methods are preferred.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent can also be used to solve a system of nonlinear equations.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Below is an example that shows how to use the gradient descent to solve for three unknown variables, *x*1, *x*2, and *x*3.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] This example shows one iteration of the gradient descent.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] This can be done with any of a variety of line search algorithms.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] is a sizable decrease in the objective function.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Further steps would reduce its value further until an approximate solution to the system was found.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:response-surface-methodology/steepest-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
